    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-09-25T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-09-25T05:00:00-05:00" n="660" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d660">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.51/9–2554: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 660<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France (<persName corresp="#p_DILLONCD1"
                            type="from">Dillon</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d660fn1">Repeated to London for the Secretary, who was there
                        to attend the Nine-Power Conference, Sept. 28–Oct. 3, 1954; regarding this
                        conference, see the editorial note, <ref target="frus1952-54v05p2#pg_1848"
                            >vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, Part 2, p. 1848</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-09-25T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 25, 1954—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1272. <persName corresp="#p_MENDSFRANCEP1">Mendes</persName> in preparation for
                    difficulties he will face on return of Parliament has launched press campaign to
                    effect that US Government in general and Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> in particular are engaged in
                    attempt to overthrow his government.<note n="2" xml:id="d660fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_MENDSFRANCEP1">Mendès-France</persName>’s anger at
                            <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> was partially due to
                            <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName>’ refusal to visit
                        Paris on his brief trip to Europe, Sept. 16–17, during which he met with
                        Chancellor <persName corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName> in Bonn and
                        then with Foreign Secretary <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> in
                        London; for documentation on <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>’ trip and <persName corresp="#p_MENDSFRANCEP1"
                            >Mendès-France</persName>’s reaction to it, see <ref
                            target="frus1952-54v05p2#pg_1195">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, Part
                            2, pp. 1195</ref> ff.</note> His obvious motive is to rally chauvinistic
                    and nationalistic feeling to his side as he did so successfully after Brussels.
                    I feel that this <persName corresp="#p_MENDSFRANCEP1">Mendes</persName> tactic
                    must be borne constantly in mind and that no opportunity should be given him to
                    imply that US or its representatives have treated France with anything other
                    than correct politeness.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DILLONCD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dillon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
